<content>
<para id="fs-id2020400">The immune system can be divided into two related mechanisms to kill pathogens: the innate immune response, which is relatively rapid but nonspecific and thus not always effective, and the adaptive immune response, which is slower in its development during an initial infection with a pathogen, but is highly specific and effective at attacking a wide range of pathogens (<link target-id="fig-ch22_02_01" document=""/>).</para><figure id="fig-ch22_02_01"><title>Cooperation between Innate and Adaptive Immune Responses </title><media id="fs-id1883630" alt="This figure shows a lateral view of a human face in the top left. A magnified callout shows the germinal center of the palatine tonsil. Another magnified view shows how the innate immune system works.">
