<section id="fs-id1700696">
<title>Cells of the Innate Immune Response</title>
<para id="fs-id2305166">A phagocyte is a cell that can surround and engulf a particle or cell, a process called <term>phagocytosis</term>. The phagocytes of the immune system engulf other particles or cells, either to clean an area of pieces of cells, old cells, or to kill pathogenic organisms such as bacteria. The phagocytes are the body’s fast acting, first line of immunological defense against organisms that have broken into barrier defenses and have entered the capable of being hurt tissues of the body.</para><table id="eip-271" summary="Table 2">
